##Taegu tensed, Osaka Calm | a tale of two cities

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Yu Xiaoqing, reporter, thepaper.cn

Recently, the situation of prevention and control of new crown pneumonia in South Korea and Japan is becoming more and more serious, which has attracted the attention of the international community.

As of 9:00 am on February 28,256 new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed in South Korea, bringing the total to 2,022 and 13 deaths, according to the latest report from the Korean Central Epidemic Prevention Department.

South Korea's Daegu city, the epicenter of the outbreak, saw its sharpest one-day increase Monday. On the same day, South Korea added 505 cases nationwide, Daegu accounted for more than 80% . Currently, more than 60 percent of South Korea's cases are concentrated in Taegu. And Taegu's medical resources have been overloaded for days. A 74-year-old man with a confirmed case of new coronavirus died Thursday after receiving first aid treatment in a hospital after his condition deteriorated during self-isolation in his home. This has raised concerns that the lack of beds could lead to more deaths.

Also on the 27th, due to the emergence of new pneumonia patients in the South Korean and US militaries, the South Korean Joint Staff Headquarters and the South korean-us joint military command said that due to the impact of the new pneumonia epidemic, South Korea and the US decided to postpone the original joint military exercises scheduled for early March. It is the first time that South Korea and the United States have postponed joint military exercises because of an epidemic of infectious diseases.

As of this press release, Japan has not yet reported new cases of coronavirus infection, but according to statistics on the 27th, including confirmed cases on the cruise ship "Diamond Princess" , Japan has a cumulative total of 919 confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia, 8 deaths from new coronary pneumonia.

Tokyo's Disneyland and Osaka's Universal Studios announced Monday that they would be closed from Feb. 29 to March 15 as the outbreak spread. On the same day, the Ministry of Education, Science and Technology of Japan issued a notice on February 28 to the prefectural education committees throughout the country, asking all primary and secondary schools to suspend classes. Shinzō Abe, the Prime Minister, told the Lower House of parliament that "it is extremely important to control the rate at which the epidemic is spreading" and he hoped the public would understand the call for the suspension.

But Japanese media reported that the Anbe Administration's sudden decision not only increased public unease in Japan, but also caught schools and parents off guard. The ministry's announcement has also left education commissions across the country with the authority to suspend classes facing tough decisions, with local governments concerned that the suspension could lead to greater chaos.

However, as severe as the epidemic was, it was a different scene in the lives of the people in the two cities of Daegu and ŌSAKA. Xiao Yang, a doctoral student studying abroad at Gyeongbuk University in Daegu city, South Korea, has felt firsthand for two weeks the heightened sense of tension surrounding the outbreak, but a doctoral student at Osaka University in Japan, who told The Paper stories about different wars in the two cities, was deemed "too nervous" by his tutors.

Daegu: My "Workaholic" professor won't come to school either

I am Xiao Yang from Gyeongbuk University in South Korea. I am studying for my Ph. D. in literature and Information Science.

On my way back to Taegu from the mainland on February 5, I noticed that the passengers on the bus from Incheon Airport to Taegu were not wearing masks, and I had been invited to live with them in Seoul, at that time, the whole of Korea did not pay special attention to this epidemic.

After returning to Daegu, I received a request from the school's Department of International Exchange for me to stay home for as long as possible for 14 days. I was in the middle of a move, so I went to my old rental house to get my stuff before the quarantine. I distinctly remember being in a taxi and being reminded by the driver to close the window to prevent me from catching cold. After my 14-day home quarantine ended, when the outbreak began in South Korea, especially in Taegu, on February 19, and again on February 20, when I took a taxi, the driver had to open the window to keep the air flowing.

Now the school has been postponed until mid-march and all public libraries, museums and churches in Daegu have been closed. After the outbreak, I only went out twice, to my school's research lab. Although each time I will go to my classmates and teachers in advance of the email, please do not worry about my arrival, but I can always feel that everyone will deliberately keep a certain distance. My classmates told me that my "workaholic" professor, who usually comes to school almost every day, has stopped coming.

Now, almost everyone on Taegu street is wearing a mask, but you can still feel that people are working and going to work, I noticed that there were disinfection notices posted in front of the restaurant, and there were no customers, but a friend told me, the pubs that open at night seem to be doing well. Do people think alcohol can be disinfected?

To be honest, I don't see a lot of targeted prevention and control. As far as I know, South Korean citizens receive regular text messages reminding them of the outbreak, and there are also loudspeakers broadcasting from the vicinity of each residential area to remind them to wear masks and pay attention to ventilation and hygiene. In addition, the government will provide masks in a planned way, and now masks are in short supply. There is a long line of people buying masks. I also saw Korean friends hoarding a bunch of masks for photos to show off their wealth.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some of the goods on the network platform have been sold out

After Taegu's "super-event" , the number of people buying online has increased significantly in recent days, and delivery workers are presumably busier. Most of the next day delivery is done before 7:00 am, we can open the door at any time to receive the goods, they show the delivery through the shopping platform, users receive the problem can also be resolved through the network platform, do not need to meet. This quick delivery service was popular, but some foods were quickly out of stock. So in addition to fresh food, dry goods and so on I will choose the general delivery, it will take about two to three days.

A few days ago, the usual delivery man knocked on my door and I asked him to leave the goods at the door to avoid contact. He said he needed a signature, so I put on a mask and opened the door. He was a tall, thin, middle-aged man who had water on his raincoat and helmet when it rained. Although the helmet had a windscreen, it could be seen that his hair and collar were wet and his lips were so dry that they seemed to peel and Split Open, he's obviously been working a long time, and he looks tired. I signed my name to thank him, and he just said good-bye and left.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In Taegu, it is already common for people to buy goods by express delivery rather than going out

Now, Chinese students return to South Korea after 14 days of home quarantine observation, we are generally very cooperative.

After the outbreak in Taegu, many international students began to think about returning home, but I will continue to stay at home for a while.

ŌSAKA: I was worried about the epidemic. My Japanese friends said I was "worrying too much. "

I am Osaka University, currently a phd candidate in disaster reconstruction, and I am surrounded by Japanese friends who are beginning to worry about the development of a newly diagnosed case of pneumonia in my city, Ōsaka, but my intuitive feeling is that we can not see the actual action, especially young people, can be said in addition to wearing masks, everyone's life is still very normal.

On the 26th, some large-scale events such as concerts began to stop in Tokyo. Before, the young Japanese people around me were planning how to go to Tokyo to see the concerts, now they're saying, "if it wasn't canceled, it would've happened. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Even in Ōsaka, face masks have become a highly sought-after commodity

A very intuitive change is that when I went out last week, about one-third of the people on the street were wearing masks, but now nearly 80 percent of the people are wearing masks, face Masks and hand sanitizers are therefore in demand and can not even be bought. I was the only one in the grocery store who wore a mask, and none of my Japanese colleagues did.

In ŌSAKA, Chinese students try to avoid going out, but my Japanese friends give me the impression that they are very "calm" and shop normally. They say they are also concerned about the epidemic, but the death rate of NCP in China is not very high, many of the patients died of underlying diseases and older. I told them I didn't want the Japanese epidemic to get worse, and they said I was "overthinking" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The pharmacy in Ōsaka puts up a sign saying the staff will wear masks, but please don't worry

Some Japanese companies are now adopting a "staggered-peak-to-work" model, but my friends are using the staggered-peak-to-work time to go to the gym. For them, the staggered-peak-to-work time does not seem to be about prevention and control of the epidemic.

As far as I can see, ŌSAKA has not taken more preventive measures, nor has it noticed any measures taken to measure the body temperature of people in places including public transport facilities.

The Osaka University updates the situation every two days to send to every student, and conducts a live online outbreak prevention and control study session. The school's Flash report warns that anyone with a fever should be quarantined at home, and it includes contact numbers for clinics.

The overall feeling is that Japan is relying on corporate and individual decisions to prevent and control the outbreak, so much so that it's not particularly clear what to do. Japanese singer Takanori Nishikawa also complained online on the 26th that he is not sure whether the concert will continue, criticizing the government for not giving people a clear message. Starting from the 29th, schools outside high schools will be closed in ŌSAKA. I also took note of the announcement by Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe that primary and secondary schools across the country will be closed from March 2nd. But I feel that in response to these decisions, people complain more.

Chinese students studying in Japan are now united. Everyone will exchange masks. I also have the idea of returning to China, the Chinese students heard about it and helped me find the N95 mask. When I emailed my mentor about my desire to return to China, he didn't say yes, implying that I was too nervous. Now, I have inquired good if after returning to my hometown Jiangsu, oneself should according to the regulation to do what matter. I'm GonNa go talk to my mentor again in person today.
